INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '673e63e5-d81b-49e2-b8a2-9783856f69b0',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Hono Testing — Unit vs Integration with app.request()$escape$,
  $escape$Hono's `app.request()` is the unit testing backbone — it invokes your route handler directly, returning a standard `Response` without spinning up a server. No `supertest`, no HTTP polyfill needed. To mock auth middleware, prepend `app.use()` in test setup to short-circuit JWT validation and inject a stub `userId` via `c.set()`.

Integration tests are different: use `serve()` from `@hono/node-server` (or Bun's native server), fire real `fetch()` requests, and tear down in `afterAll`. This validates middleware ordering, error serialization, and CORS headers end-to-end — things `app.request()` can miss.

For test databases, point `TEST_DATABASE_URL` at a dedicated schema. In `beforeAll`, run migrations via your ORM's push command or a raw `pg` client. In `afterEach`, truncate tables — never drop them. Dropping forces schema recreation on every test, which is slow and fragile.

The rule: unit-test handler logic and response shapes via `app.request()` with mocked middleware bindings; integration-test only the HTTP contract. Never duplicate both layers for the same route.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Hono } from 'hono'
import { describe, it, expect, beforeAll } from 'vitest'

const app = new Hono()

// Stub auth middleware for unit tests
app.use('*', (c, next) => { c.set('userId', 'user-123'); return next() })
app.get('/me', (c) => c.json({ id: c.get('userId') }))

describe('GET /me', () => {
  it('returns stubbed user id', async () => {
    const res = await app.request('/me')
    expect(res.status).toBe(200)
    expect(await res.json()).toEqual({ id: 'user-123' })
  })
})$escape$,
